# React & TypeScript rules

## Core principles

### Value Abstraction Above Repetition

- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks
- Create generic components instead of duplicating code
- Use TypeScript generics for flexible, type-safe abstractions
- Prefer composition over duplication

### Don't Overcomplicate

- Keep components simple and focused
- Use existing solutions (shadcn/ui) over building from scratch
- Prefer clear, readable code over clever one-liners

## Coding standards

### Naming conventions

- Use kebab case for all files/directories
- Test files end with \*.spec.ts(x)
- Favor named exports for components
- Use PascalCase for component names
- Use camelCase for hooks and utility functions

### React

- Prefer `useCallback` for event handlers passed as props
- Use custom hooks for complex state logic
- Optimize React renders
- Prefer const arrow functions over traditional function syntax

### TypeScript

- Use strict mode
- Use interface for object structures, declaration merging
- Use type for unions and intersections
- If in doubt, use a type instead of interface
- Avoid enums, instead use const objects with a typescript helper to create unions types
- Implement proper generic types
- Using proper type inference
- Avoiding 'any' type unless absolutely necessary
- Avoid type assertions unless absolutely necessary
- Creating reusable type utilities"
- Prefer arrow functions over traditional function syntax

## UI and styling

- Use shadcn components where possible
- Use tailwind for any customizations
